      <h2>Why this stuff matters</h2>
      <p>People sometimes wonder why scientists spend years studying fruit flies, worms, or yeast. It might not seem relevant to everyday life. But all life on Earth shares a common ancestor, which means we share genes — even with distant relatives like flies and yeast. A gene that causes cancer in humans often has a counterpart in these organisms, and because they're cheaper and faster to study, scientists can test treatments in them first. The connections extend well beyond medicine into agriculture, conservation, forensics, and more — here are some examples.</p>

      <h3>Medicine and disease</h3>
      <ul>
        <li>Drug discovery — every new drug must be tested in living organisms before human trials. Phylogeny guides which ones: mice share many disease genes with us because they're fellow mammals, so nearly every approved drug was tested in rodents first. But even <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Zebrafish" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">zebrafish</a> (vertebrates with see-through eggs that let researchers watch organs form), <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Caenorhabditis_elegans" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer"><em>C. elegans</em> worms</a> (only 302 neurons, yet they share key aging and disease genes with us), and <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Drosophila_melanogaster" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">fruit flies</a> are used for early drug screening because they're fast to breed and still share key disease pathways with humans</li>
        <li>Cancer — two-thirds of genes implicated in human cancers have a counterpart in <a href="https://pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/articles/PMC6405444/" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">fruit flies</a>, Nobel Prize-winning research on the cell cycle was done in <a href="https://www.nature.com/scitable/topicpage/l-h-hartwell-s-yeast-a-model-808/" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">yeast</a>, and programmed cell death — how cells "decide" to die, which fails in tumors — was discovered in <em>C. elegans</em> worms</li>
        <li>Vaccine development — WHO selects influenza vaccine strains each year based on <a href="https://www.science.org/doi/10.1126/sciadv.abp9185" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">phylogenetic analysis of circulating viruses</a></li>
        <li>Epidemiology — phylogenetics <a href="https://www.smithsonianmag.com/science-nature/tracking-2014-ebola-outbreak-through-its-genes-180952487/" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">traced the 2014 Ebola outbreak's spread</a> in detail, was applied on a large scale for SARS-CoV2, and helped track a <a href="https://www.wired.com/2013/01/ff-kpc-superbug-nih/" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">deadly superbug outbreak at the NIH</a></li>
        <li>Food safety — <a href="https://www.propublica.org/article/how-propublica-used-genomic-sequencing-data-to-track-an-ongoing-salmonella-outbreak" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">whole-genome phylogenetics links Salmonella outbreaks</a> to specific contaminated food sources</li>
        <li>Horizontal gene transfer — detecting <a href="https://www.scientificamerican.com/blog/observations/soil-may-help-pathogens-make-us-sick/" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">antibiotic resistance genes that jumped from soil bacteria to pathogens</a></li>
        <li>Medical safety — <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Horseshoe_crab" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">horseshoe crabs</a> (more closely related to spiders than crabs) have blue blood containing a clotting agent used for decades to test vaccines and medical equipment for bacterial contamination</li>
        <li>Metagenomics — <a href="https://www.scientificamerican.com/article/gut-bacteria-gene-complement-d/" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">classifying the thousands of microbial species</a> in a gut microbiome sample</li>
        <li>Comparative genomics — <a href="https://www.nature.com/articles/nature13992" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">comparing human and mouse genomes</a> reveals conserved regulatory elements</li>
      </ul>

      <h3>Gene therapies</h3>
      <p>Many breakthrough medical technologies came from studying other organisms.</p>
      <ul>
        <li>CRISPR — a bacterial immune system repurposed to precisely edit human genes. The FDA <a href="https://www.statnews.com/2023/12/08/fda-approves-casgevy-crispr-based-medicine-for-treatment-of-sickle-cell-disease/" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">approved the first CRISPR therapy</a> for sickle cell disease, with trials ongoing for cancers and inherited blindness</li>
        <li>RNA interference — discovered in <em>C. elegans</em> worms (<a href="https://www.nobelprize.org/prizes/medicine/2006/press-release/" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">Nobel Prize 2006</a>), now the basis of approved drugs that silence disease-causing genes</li>
        <li>Antisense oligonucleotides — synthetic molecules that block specific gene messages. <a href="https://www.ninds.nih.gov/about-ninds/what-we-do/impact/ninds-contributions-approved-therapies/nusinersen-spinrazar-spinal-muscular-atrophy-sma" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">Spinraza</a>, the first approved treatment for spinal muscular atrophy, uses this approach</li>
        <li>Transposon engineering — "jumping genes," first discovered by Barbara McClintock in corn, now harnessed to insert therapeutic genes into human cells. The <a href="https://www.nature.com/articles/s41434-021-00254-w" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">Sleeping Beauty transposon</a> was reconstructed from ancient fish genomes for use in cancer immunotherapy</li>
      </ul>

      <h3>Agriculture and environment</h3>
      <ul>
        <li>Agriculture — <a href="https://daily.jstor.org/can-crops-wild-relatives-save-troubled-agriculture/" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">wild relatives</a> of crops like wheat, rice, and tomato are crossed with cultivated varieties to introduce disease resistance and stress tolerance. Modern efforts go further: <a href="https://link.springer.com/article/10.1186/s13059-020-02224-8" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">pangenome projects</a> now sequence dozens of wild relatives to catalogue the full genetic diversity of a crop species, revealing thousands of genes lost during domestication that breeders can reintroduce</li>
        <li>Conservation — the <a href="https://www.nature.com/articles/s41586-020-2561-9" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">tuatara</a>, sole survivor of its order, is prioritized because it represents a unique evolutionary lineage</li>
        <li>Coevolution — <a href="https://insideecology.com/2025/12/02/figs-and-their-wasps-a-75-million-year-partnership-that-may-be-the-first-known-plant-animal-holobiont/" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">figs and fig wasps</a> have coevolved for over 75 million years. Darwin predicted a moth with a foot-long tongue must exist to pollinate a deep orchid — it was found decades later. Mitochondria, the energy factories in every cell of your body, were originally free-living bacteria that merged with our ancestors ~2 billion years ago</li>
      </ul>

      <h3>Biotechnology and discovery</h3>
      <ul>
        <li>Forensics — <a href="https://www.sciencedaily.com/releases/2011/03/110307151913.htm" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">phylogenetics of Bacillus anthracis</a> helped trace the 2001 anthrax letter attacks back to a specific lab flask, one of the first major uses of microbial forensics</li>
        <li>Antibiotics — most antibiotics were originally discovered by <a href="https://www.acs.org/education/whatischemistry/landmarks/selmanwaksman.html" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">screening soil microorganisms</a> and their relatives, including penicillin, streptomycin, and tetracycline</li>
        <li>Biotechnology — in 1982, engineered <em>E. coli</em> bacteria produced <a href="https://pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/articles/PMC8152450/" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">the first recombinant human insulin</a>, replacing animal-sourced insulin for diabetics. The same approach now produces human growth hormone, clotting factors, and many other medicines</li>
        <li>PCR — <a href="https://www.nps.gov/articles/thermophile-yell.htm" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">Taq polymerase</a>, an enzyme found in heat-tolerant bacteria in Yellowstone hot springs, enabled PCR — a technique that makes millions of copies of a tiny DNA sample so there's enough to detect and analyze, used in nearly every area of modern biology and medicine</li>
        <li>Ancestral reconstruction — scientists can <a href="https://www.nature.com/articles/nrg1324" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">resurrect ancient proteins</a> to study how they evolved, and engineer more stable versions for <a href="https://www.nature.com/articles/nbt.3677" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">drug development</a> and <a href="https://www.nature.com/articles/s41929-018-0159-5" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">industrial enzymes</a></li>
        <li>Convergent evolution — when <a href="https://www.science.org/content/article/bats-and-dolphins-evolved-echolocation-same-way" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">bats and dolphins independently evolved echolocation</a> using the same gene mutations, it revealed which molecular designs are truly optimal — guiding protein engineering and drug design</li>
      </ul>

      <p>Of course, not everything here started with a practical goal. Much of it began as basic curiosity — scientists trying to figure out how the world works. But that's how science operates: open-ended inquiry has a way of producing breakthroughs no one saw coming.</p>
